## Recurring Meeting — How It Works

### Master Event

- When a recurring meeting is created, the **master event must NOT be pushed to Salesforce**.
- The plugin sends the **master event to ORCAS only**.
- ORCAS stores the master, then on its next cycle connects to Exchange, retrieves all occurrences, and **pushes them to Salesforce**.

### Occurrences

- ORCAS creates and manages all occurrences in Salesforce.
- The plugin **never pushes occurrences directly** to Salesforce.
- This was a point of confusion between Roman and Sanika — confirmed: the plugin does **not** directly push occurrences to Salesforce at any point.

### Amendments & Modifications — Clarified

This was a key point of confusion. The original notes said *“amendments to recurring meetings are handled by the plugin only”* which seemed to contradict the modified occurrences row in the routing table. Here is the correct understanding confirmed by Vipin:

- The **plugin handles the amendment** (i.e., it is the one pushing the change to Salesforce).
- But it **must also notify ORCAS** and record it as “synced” in the ORCAS database.
- This applies to **all meetings**, not just recurring — because when “sync meetings” is selected, the plugin captures any and every modification.
- The two steps (plugin pushes + notifies ORCAS) happen together — they are not contradictory.

### Modified Occurrences (Exceptions)

- If a single occurrence within a recurring series is modified, the plugin sends **full details to ORCAS**.
- ORCAS then pushes the change to Salesforce and stores the SF ID.

### Occurrence Deletions

- If an occurrence is deleted, the plugin sends a **delete notification to ORCAS**.
- ORCAS deletes it from Salesforce and marks it as deleted in the database.
- If the plugin were to delete directly without telling ORCAS, the sync engine would never know the event was deleted — causing data inconsistency.

-----

## Why the Plugin Must Notify ORCAS

- ORCAS runs a **background sync cycle** that checks Outlook for any changes since the last run.
- If the plugin modifies or syncs something to Salesforce **without notifying ORCAS**, the sync engine will detect the change in its next cycle and attempt to sync it again — causing a **double-sync conflict**.
- To prevent this, anything the plugin syncs to Salesforce must be **recorded in the ORCAS database as “synced”** so the sync engine skips it entirely.
- Most of the time, the sync engine will do nothing — its main job is handling **new recurring master events**. Everything else is handled by the plugin, as long as it properly notifies ORCAS.

-----

## Salesforce ID — New Requirement (from Sanika & Roman discussion)

- Previously, the plugin never needed to track the **Salesforce ID** — it was not useful to it.
- Now that ORCAS is in the picture, the plugin must:
1. Push the event to Salesforce.
1. **Capture the SF ID** returned by Salesforce.
1. Send the SF ID along with other fields (user email, Exchange ID, etc.) to ORCAS.
- ORCAS uses the SF ID to identify and update the correct record in Salesforce on future cycles.
- Sanika confirmed that Salesforce always returns an ID after a save — Roman needs to ensure this is captured and passed through.

-----

## Recurring Flag — Roman’s Responsibility

- Roman must **explicitly track the recurring flag** in the plugin.
- This flag determines whether the master event is held back from Salesforce and routed to ORCAS instead.
- This is considered a **minor change** but is critical to correct routing behavior.

-----

## Event Routing Summary

|Event Type                         |Plugin does                                     |ORCAS does                                    |
|-----------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|
|**Single create/update/delete**    |Pushes to SF directly, notifies ORCAS with SF ID|Stores record, skips on background cycle      |
|**Recurring master**               |Sends to ORCAS only                             |Stores master, pushes occurrences via Exchange|
|**Exception (modified occurrence)**|Sends full details to ORCAS                     |Pushes to SF, stores SF ID                    |
|**Occurrence deletion**            |Sends delete notification to ORCAS              |Deletes from SF, marks deleted                |

